My whole life I’ve found myself constantly saying things like “I need to get my life together” no matter where I’ve been in my life— some way, some how there’s always some area of my life that will need improvement. Whether that be my fitness, finances, my relationships with others, my spiritual life, and the list goes on.. 

But today, as I worked toward my goal on the stair master, I listened to this motivational video on YouTube and it went like this: 
“I never want to get to the place where I’ve got it all figured out. I still want to keep learning, I still want to keep growing and I still want to be a student and I still want to be in a learning curve and I still want to value people and I still want to walk into their life and say, ‘look, you have something that, if I could just ask the right question, you could impart to me that would help me, that would allow me to become a better person myself.’”

All of life is about becoming, learning, growing, getting better. The biggest room in this world is the room for improvement. We are all in a process. And that process will end the day you take your last breath. You should never get to a place where you feel like you’re satisfied or you know it all because at that point, you are stopping yourself from learning more and becoming more. And you should never postpone your happiness until you get some place you want to be in life because there will always be a next big thing to go after. You will only be as happy as you make up your mind to be right now 🦋

Working on myself while being a mom has been the hardest yet most rewarding part of my fitness journey. Before pregnancy, I had gotten to a point in my fitness journey where I felt like I had it all figured out. I was very committed to myself and my goals. But after becoming a mom, I felt my commitment shifted to my little human. I was and still am worried about him 24/7 and I feel like had I not been so consistent with my fitness journey before having a baby, I would not have had the hope in myself to begin recommitting myself to my body after pregnancy. I never looked at my journey as getting back to the old Dani, but rather reinventing Dani 2.0, Dani the mom. I let the old me go and focused on building the new me because that person was gone the moment I birthed a new life - that is exactly how I felt, like I was reborn again. This is not the end of your health and fitness journey, this is only the beginning! This is where you get to show yourself and your baby that you’re the real deal! That you CAN do whatever you set your mind to; it’s possible for you! And you don’t need to do it by yourself, I’m here to help you! Let’s get you started on your new era! 3 things that have helped me on my postpartum journey 🤎

I. acceptance —— there’ve been many things that I’ve simply had to accept about myself after becoming a mom- the main part being my body. The stretch marks in my belly area, the loose skin, the boobies.. all things that in the beginning had me looking in the mirror side ways like “wow, this is really my body now..” and it’s okay for you to miss that old version of you sometimes but at some point you just have to make peace with the fact that now you’re in a different state of your life and for many women that also means, a different body. 

ll. setting realistic expectations for myself
specially here on instagram, where you’re following other fitness women who get pregnant and you’re astonished by their body transformation and by how fast they achieved it. I stopped comparing myself to other women’s postpartum journey/ body. Because every woman is different, every woman doesn’t gain the same amount of weight during pregnancy, every woman’s skin elasticity is not the same. I also stopped comparing myself or setting goals based on the old me (before pregnancy) and just set goals based on how I could get better and improve my current body. 
*remember all you have is all you have - so if you curse everything you’ve got… you’re left with nothing to work with or build on.* 

III. F L E X I B I L I T Y —— ouuu chile this is a good one! Before becoming a mom I thrives on structure and having a routine that I followed daily but being a mom a lot of your days are unpredictable. Things that make it so much harder for me to adhere to a certain schedule are 1. Co-sleeping and 2. Pumping. Those two things are by biggest obstacles. Oh and always thinking that Devin needed to be either watched by someone or asleep in order for me to exercise. I started getting creative and having a no problem attitude, working out at home with Devin had become a fun thing to do for the both of us!

a pumping queen 👑✨ lol in the beginning it took a while for me to get the hang of pumping while on the go but as I got information from other mommas, I became more confident and comfortable with this whole pumping lifestyle. Here are some tips if you’re pumping on the go. 

✨ have a cooler bag with an ice pack in it and empty bottles to pour the milk that you pump. 

✨always keep your ice pack in the freezer that way if you’re running our of the house, you can just grab it and put it in your pumping bag 

✨ if you pump milk and don’t have somewhere to keep it cold, you can keep it at room temp for 4 hours until you either put it in  the fridge/ cooler or feed it to your baby

✨ a hands free pump works better for me when I’m on the go bc I can just pop them on and do whatever it is I need to do. I believe you should still have a stronger pump for home (I use medela electric pump) but it’s good to keep a set of hands free (i use mom cozy) for on the go

✨how do I reuse my pump if I’m somewhere where I can’t clean it? I always rinse and then keep my pump parts inside a ziplock and and inside my cooler bag for a few hours between uses to help slow the growth of bacteria. 

Do you guys have any more tips you’d like to add? ⬇️

Summer Pasta Salad recipe

Dressing Ingredients:
mayonnaise
white wine or plain vinegar
salt
freshly ground black pepper

Creamy Pasta Salad Recipe

In a large pot, cook the pasta according to the directions on the package, adding a generous tablespoon or so of salt to the water as it cooks.

Just before the noodles are done cooking, add the broccoli to the pot. Let the broccoli boil for about 30 seconds and then drain everything into a large strainer. Rinse well with cold water.

 Stir together the mayonnaise, vinegar, salt, and pepper in a large mixing bowl.

Add the cooked pasta and broccoli to the bowl and stir well to coat.

Add the, pepper and onions and stir again.

Taste and adjust seasonings, if needed. Cover and refrigerate until ready to serve. Stir again just before serving.

“Life is our gift to us that God has given us and how we live our lives is our gift to God. What kind of gift are you formulating?” JR 🤍

While I type this caption, my arm feels numb as it does every morning from the weight of your growing head laying on it. I’ve accepted my back pain and neck pain from always laying facing you and keeping you comfortable while you look for me every night in your sleep. Truth is, it’s all worth it when I see your little eyes open in the morning and closing in peace once you realize I’m right next to you. 

These days when people ask how I’m doing and I’m like “oh I’m so much better now” people usually have sort of a confused or curious look on their face and ask why or if something was going on with me and I usually tell them no it’s just adjusting to life as a new mom and they’re like “ahhhhh yea” looking kind of sad for me. 

The truth is I’m so incredibly happy with this one part of my life that it overarches all the lack or unhappiness. It’s like I can’t stay stuck in something too long because the minute he smiles at me, my heart feels so warm and it gives me such a reassuring feeling that everything will fall into place as long as I can keep seeing that smile and watching him grow.

Being a mom was something I wasn’t planning. And I remember bursting into tears when I went to my GYN and I found out I was pregnant, asking God why, telling him I was not ready… I will never forget that phone call with my mom that lasted about an hour, her telling me that this is a blessing, that I don’t need to be sad because this is actually a great thing, that we would figure this out together and that she was gonna be with me every step of the way. I could cry thinking of that time, because there I was so scared of what was next, and now I cannot see my life without him. He won’t remember any of this, but I will forever cherish it in my heart of hearts. And it makes me wonder about all the beautiful moments I don’t remember that my mom had with me, doing it all for me, loving me, carrying my on her hip and going about her daily tasks. And then I think what must it be like for her now seeing her little girl relive that with her own baby.. The cycle of life. The cycle of love. Unconditional love.

When I was pregnant I used to say I was gonna breastfeed my baby until my boobs fell off lol. But after seeing the reality of breastfeeding and how not every mom gets the same breastfeeding experience, I quickly understood that it’s not all that easy and it was going to take a lot of will power and emotional strength on my end to keep up with pumping milk for my baby since he would reject my boob (unless he was sleeping). However, to me it was such an honor and so satisfying to not only make him his own milk just for him but also to see him drink it. I was literally his source of food and although that put a lot of pressure on me, it felt so darn good!!! I thank God for allowing me to keep up with my baby for an entire year & for being able to latch him at night when we would Cosleep (we still cosleep) just for me to get that bonding experience because I know there are so many Mom’s who were robbed of that due to so many different reasons (latching problems, production problems, detachment from baby and so much more) 

Anyway, it’s been such a bittersweet feeling deciding to stop. It was actually not a firm decision, it was more like I started transitioning him to cow’s milk, so slowly I began to pump less times a day until I saw he was not having any issues with drinking his cow milk and that’s when I began feeling like it was okay to stop. The extra time I get to not have to pump while he naps or not have to go everywhere with my pumping bag does feel prettty good, but nothing compared to the joy of knowing I had his next bottle of milk in the fridge waiting for him 🩵☁️ 

Disclaimer: No you don’t need to stop pumping after the first year. I would’ve loved to keep pumping until my baby decided to stop drinking breastmilk but as we approached the 1 year mark, I began to struggle to keep up with his eating and I was also starting to cook foods for him so it started to become mentally draining to pump while trying to make and feed him solids which most of the time he didn’t want because he was so picky at first. You do what you feel is best for you and your kid and please save your judgment towards other moms who are also just trying to do their best.

Little recap of my mornings lately 🤍 Posting the full workout later ⚡️⚡️
I love it here ☁️☁️☁️

legs & glutes + cardio 

warmup (3 sets) 
20 butt kicks 
15 squats 
10 lunges 

legs & glutes (3 sets) 
10 dumbbell squats 
10 dumbbell hip thrusts + 5 without weight 
10 single leg dumbbell hip thrusts + 5 without weight (each side) 
10 bulgarian split squats 

cardio stair master
30 seconds fast paced 
30 seconds rest 
repeat 5x 

note:
- I was adding weight with each set so I would start off at a comfortable weight and every set I would grab a dumbbell that was 5 lbs heavier. 
- for the stair master after I completed the 5x I kept going at a average pace that was comfortable for me until I reached 100 floors just cause I always like to do 100 floors.

Whew chile!! This week was fenomenal!!! Worked out 6/7 days and woke up at 4 am 5/7 days ☑️ feeling unstoppable! Hoping to keep this rhythm going 🤞🏼 some days I had to do it on 4-5 hours of sleep but I did it anyway and it feels darn good to get to the end of the week a more disciplined version of myself! Now I get to rest until doing it all over again 💪🏼 

I’ve fought myself so hard to get to this place in my mind! This place where it actually feels good to get up and work on myself, where I’m not dragging myself out of bed anymore but waking up ready to tackle the day! I haven’t felt this way since before pregnancy! And I just pray that God keeps me going man. I know that all things are possible through Christ who strengthens me 🫀 

Have a great weekend fam! And thanks for all the love on my page & my journey! Just remember, it’s possible for YOU too! And I am here to help! (link is on my bio when you’re ready to take that first step)

Editing these videos realizing that … one day I’m going to look back at them and realize that these were the best days. What a blessing it is to have be a mom and have a mom… what a blessing it is to have so many things to keep you busy and make you feel like a valuable human being. What a blessing it is to be the nurturer of your family while still having your own nurturer with you to help you through it. I love my life just as it is and I just want to take a moment to remind you, that it’s all temporary… one day, you’re gonna miss it. You’re gonna miss feeling so depended on. You’re gonna miss having someone who demands your attention. You’re gonna miss having that someone in your life who will always be there for you no matter what 🩷
